Network Performance Comparison¶

To compare our network models, we will use a McNemar test. This allows us to statistically evaluate if there is a significant difference in the proportion of errors made by the classifier, and additionally does not require us to retrain the model n times for a sample size and set of metrics (which saves a ton of training time and computational power).

We will define a helper function to calculate the McNemar test statistic, and can then perform hypothesis testing as follows: \begin{aligned}H_{0}&:~p_{b}=p_{c}\\H_{1}&:~p_{b}\neq p_{c}\end{aligned}

The test statistic is calculated as: \begin{aligned}\chi ^{2}={(b-c)^{2} \over b+c}\end{aligned}

where a, b, c, and d are counts of correct and incorrect predictions as can be found at the following source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McNemar%27s_test

Then, we can use the McNemar statistic as a chi-squared value with one degree of freedom.

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc

def plotROC(preds_m1, preds_m2, trueVals, label=None):
    # Compute micro-average ROC curve and ROC area
    
    false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(trueVals, preds_m1)
    roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
    
    plt.plot(false_positive_rate,true_positive_rate, color='red',label = 'CNN Large = %0.2f' % roc_auc)
    
    false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate, thresholds = roc_curve(trueVals, preds_m2)
    roc_auc = auc(false_positive_rate, true_positive_rate)
    
    plt.plot(false_positive_rate,true_positive_rate, color='green',label = 'GRU RNN = %0.2f' % roc_auc)
    
    
    plt.title('Receiver Op. Char.' + (label if label is not None else ""))
    plt.legend(loc = 'lower right')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],linestyle='--')
    plt.axis('tight')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    
    
def plotMulticlassROC(model1, model2):
    
    preds_m1 = model1.predict(X_test)
    preds_m2 = model2.predict(X_test)
    
    plotsOnLine = 1
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 3))
    
    for i in range(19):
        plt.subplot(1, 5, plotsOnLine)
        
        plotROC(
            preds_m1[:, i], 
            preds_m2[:, i],
            np.argmax(y_test, axis=1) == i,
            label=" class " +  str(i),
            )
        
        if plotsOnLine == 5:
            plotsOnLine = 0
        if plotsOnLine == 0:
            plt.show()
            plt.figure(figsize=(15, 3))
        plotsOnLine += 1
        
        
def calcMcNemarStatistic(model1, model2):
    preds_m1 = np.argmax(model1.predict(X_test), axis=1)
    preds_m2 = np.argmax(model2.predict(X_test), axis=1)
    
    # Get array of where each prediction was correct
    preds_m1_correct = (preds_m1 == np.argmax(y_test, axis=1)).astype(np.bool)
    preds_m2_correct = (preds_m2 == np.argmax(y_test, axis=1)).astype(np.bool)
    
    # assert lengths same
    assert len(preds_m1_correct) == len(preds_m2_correct)
    
    # a = test 1 correct and test 2 correct
    a = sum(preds_m1_correct[preds_m2_correct])
    # b = test 1 correct and test 2 incorrect
    b = sum(preds_m1_correct[ ~preds_m2_correct ])
    # c = test 1 incorrect and test 2 correct
    c = sum(preds_m2_correct[ ~preds_m1_correct ])
    # d = test 1 incorrect and test 2 incorrect
    d = sum(~preds_m1_correct[~preds_m2_correct])
    
    # ensure totals are correct
    assert (a+b+c+d == len(preds_m1_correct))
    
    # ensure that b+c >= 25 so that a chi sq can be approximated
    #assert (b+c >= 25)
    
    chisq = (b - c) ** 2
    chisq /= (b + c)
    
    return chisq

from scipy.stats import chi2 as statChiSquared
def getProb(chiSq, df=1):
    return 1 - statChiSquared.cdf(chiSq, df)

def getAccuracy(model):
    preds = model.predict(X_test)
    preds = np.argmax(preds, axis=1)
    return sum(preds == np.argmax(y_test, axis=1)) / len(preds)

from sklearn import metrics as mt

def plotConfusions(model):

    plt.figure(figsize=(13, 10))

    yhat = np.argmax(model.predict(X_test), axis=1)
    acc = mt.accuracy_score(np.argmax(y_test, axis=1), yhat)
    cm = mt.confusion_matrix(np.argmax(y_test, axis=1), yhat)
    cm = cm/np.sum(cm,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.2f')
    plt.title('Accuracy: '+str(acc))

    plt.show()
In [62]:
def fullTest(model1, model2, alpha=0.05):
    stat = calcMcNemarStatistic(model1, model2)
    prob = getProb(stat)
    print("Model Accuracy:")
    print("\tModel One:", getAccuracy(model1))
    print("\tModel Two:", getAccuracy(model2))
    print("Chi-Squared Test")
    print("\tdf=1, chi-squared val:", stat)
    print("\talpha="+str(alpha))
    print("\tProbability:", prob)
    print("\tWe " + ("REJECT" if (prob < alpha) else "FAIL TO REJECT") + " the null hypothesis, which states that the models perform similarly.")

Preprocessing Model Comparisons¶

We observe that adding preprocessing decreases performance by a statistically significant margin in every case. It appears to be better to let the neural networks / embeddings use full, unprocessed texts.
